-- South Korea, Philippines, India, Malaysia, Indonesia: Asia Bonds, Currency
-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 2011-02-06T22:58:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-06/south-korea-philippines-india-malaysia-indonesia-asia-bonds-currency.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.    Bank of Japan  Governor Masaaki Shirakawa will speak at
12:30 p.m. at the Foreign Correspondents’ Club of Japan in Tokyo.  The Cabinet Office will release at 2 p.m. in Tokyo its
preliminary report on the coincident and leading indexes for
December. The coincident index rose to 103.1 from 102.4 in
November, according to a Bloomberg News survey of economists.
The leading index gained to 101.4 from 100.6, another survey
showed.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due December
2020 was 1.280 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 82.23 per dollar at 7:47 a.m. in Tokyo.    India : The statistics office will forecast the economy
expanded 8.6 percent in the year ending March 31, according to
the median estimate in a Bloomberg survey of economists before
the data is published today.  The rupee was at 45.5975 per dollar.    South Korea : The central bank will sell 1 trillion won
($907 million) of 91-day bonds and 500 billion won of 182-day
bonds. The government will sell 1.5 trillion won of 3-year bonds.  The yield on the 5 percent debt due June 2020 was 4.72
percent. The won was at 1,103.25 per dollar.  Malaysia: The central bank will publish foreign-exchange
reserves data as of Jan. 31 today. Reserves stood at $106.5
billion as of Jan. 14.  The central bank will sell 1 billion ringgit ($330 million)
of 210-day notes and 2 billion ringgit of 128-day notes today.
It will also sell 1.5 billion ringgit of 910-day Islamic notes
and 1 billion ringgit of 128-day Islamic notes.  The ringgit was at 3.0295.    Indonesia : The economy expanded 6.3 percent in the fourth
quarter from a year earlier, according to the median estimate in
a Bloomberg survey ahead of the data due today.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 8.92
percent. The rupiah was at 8,992.    Philippines : The central bank will release foreign-exchange
reserves data for January today. Reserves stood at $62.4 billion
at the end of December.  The government is scheduled to sell a combined 8.5 billion
pesos ($194 million) of 91-, 182- and 364-day treasury bills
today.  The yield on the 5.875 percent debt due December 2020 was
6.84 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 43.765 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
